04264nam a22005175i 9780773566446DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19971997xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735664467 a10.1515/97807735664462doi  a(DE-B1597)657537  a(OCoLC)732600845  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aRA989.F8bH53 1997eb 7aMED0390002bisacsh04a362.1/1/0944091 aHickey, Daniel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLocal Hospitals in Ancien Régime France :bRationalization, Resistance, Renewal, 1530-1789 /cDaniel Hickey. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1997] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's/Associated Medical Services Studies in the History of Medicine, Health, and Society ;v500tFront Matter -- tContents -- tMaps, Tables, and Figures -- tPreface -- tGlossary of French Terms -- tIntroduction -- tBeginning Hospital Reform -- tChanges in the Organization and Direction of Town and Village Charity, 1540–1640 -- tTransferring Poor-Relief Funds to Old Soldiers: The Order of Mount Carmel and St-Lazare -- tThe Aftermath of Notre-Dame of Mount Carmel and St-Lazare: The Closures Continue -- tConsolidating and Reinforcing Local Hospitals -- tThe Hospital, the Church, and the Local Community: Control, Support, and Involvement -- tReligious Congregations and Local Hospitals: Women Working in the World -- tThe State and Hospital Reform in the Eighteenth Century: New Direction or Continued Improvisation? -- tConclusion -- tGrignan Recteurs des Pauvres, 1661–1722 -- tSeyne Recteurs of the Hospital, 1713–1750 -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries the French Crown closed down thousands of local hospices, maladreries, and small hospitals that had been refuges for the sick and poor, supposedly acting in the name of efficiency, better management, and elimination of duplicate services. Its true motive, however, was to expropriate their revenues and holdings. Hickey shows how, in spite of government efforts, a countermovement emerged that to some degree foiled the Crown's attempts to suppress local hospitals. Charitable institutions, churchmen inspired by the new message of the Catholic Reformation, women's religious congregations, and community elites defied intervention measures, resisted proposed changes, and revitalized the very type of institution the Crown was trying to shut down. Hickey's conclusions are supported by a study of eight local hospitals, which allows him to measure the impact of Crown decisions on the day-to-day functioning of these local institutions. Challenging the interpretations of Michel Foucault and other historians, Hickey throws new light on an important area of early modern French history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356644640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773566446423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773566446/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles